# Planning

Before writing a blog post, be sure to read all related resources in full so that you understand the content you will be blogging about.

After reading all related resources, choose the shape of the blog post. Here are some common shapes:

1. **Fable** - recounts an experience with a focus on elevating a lesson or insight that came from it. Excludes extreme detail when that detail isn't relevant to the lesson. Has a conclusion that distills and drives home the lesson.
2. **Essay** - synthesizes and justifies a thesis based on *multiple* instances of experience and introspection. Has a conclusion that summarizes and drives home the thesis. Essay titles should take a stance or make a claim, not just name the topic.
3. **Diary** - narrates an experience with a focus on having had the experience, without concern for a specific lesson or insight. Usually doesn't have a formal conclusion. More qualitative than the Archaelogical Record, this is a "cool story, bro" kind of post.
4. **Archaelogical Record** - recounts an experience with a focus on the factual details of the experience. Precise detail is important when details are unique to the experience and not publicly available: Readers may attempt to verify or reproduce portions of the experience themselves. Does not need a conclusion - it's just a record.
5. **Announcement** - introduces something new to an audience assumed to already care about the problem it solves. Leads with benefits, not features. Always includes a recipe - ordered steps that get the reader from zero to using the thing, inlined unless there's a good reason to link out. Tone runs warmer and more upbeat than other shapes - infectious enthusiasm, in-between "news dispatch" and "sales pitch."
6. **Guide** - orients the reader in unfamiliar or shifting territory, combining the case for why the territory matters with practical instruction for how to operate in it. Presupposes that the destination is worth the journey *and* that these particular steps are the best way to get there.

Other shapes are allowed, and encouraged when they fit the subject matter better. **ALWAYS** decide on a "shape" for the post before writing it.

## Choosing the Right Shape

Ask yourself: **Why am I writing this?**

- **"I want readers to learn from my mistake/discovery"** → Fable
- **"I want readers to consider/adopt this perspective"** → Essay  
- **"I want to share an experience that was meaningful to me"** → Diary
- **"I want readers to be able to recreate/verify what I did"** → Archaeological Record
- **"I want readers to adopt/use this thing I made"** → Announcement
- **"I want readers who want the results I got, to follow my steps to achieve it"** → Guide

If you have a lesson but worry about seeming preachy, write the Fable anyway. Readers came to a blog for perspective, not just events.

# Style

1. **Classical style:** Use classical style as mentioned by Steven Pinker and according to Thomas Turner's "Clear and Simple as the Truth," using plain English.
2. **Clever and concise tone:** Use a clever and concise, educated tone akin to Paul Graham and Martin Fowler.
    * Titles should match this style - being short, simple, sweet and if possible with a hint of wit.
3. **First person:** Write in the first person.
    * Decide whether the post would benefit from *direct address* of the reader. Maintain this choice consistently throughout the post.
4. **No emdashes:** Use hyphens instead.
5. **Avoid "it's not X, it's Y":** Don't use this construction.
6. **Show, don't tell:** Avoid meta-commentary about your own process. If you document solving six test failures, don't add a section saying "I systematically debugged each failure." The reader just watched you do it.
7. **Avoid self-congratulation:** Sections that describe "how well the work was done" are usually redundant. The quality speaks through the documented results.

## Technical Chops

1. **Strategic Code Links:** For technical posts, link strategically to actual code (use version tags when applicable). Link to solutions/fixes, not problems. Use sparingly for emphasis on interesting technical details; use triumphantly when illustrating solutions you arrived at.
2. **Foreign Term Links:** When introducing a foreign term or concept that may not be well-known, link its first major semantic mention to a definition or explanation somewhere. For common terms, this may be Wikipedia; for industry jargon or techniques, it may be a blog post or article from a recognized authority, etc.
3. **Readers don't care about test quantities:** "77/77 tests pass" - nobody cares unless the whole article is about the quantity of tests passing. This generalizes to other quantities - if the quantity itself doesn't directly contribute to the meat of the story, think hard about whether the actual number bears mentioning.

## Writing Lessons and Takeaways

When writing conclusion sections:

- **Prefer specific over generic:** "RubyGems OIDC configuration is case-sensitive on usernames" beats "Gem publishing has sharp edges"
- **Include the actionable detail:** Don't just say "tool X has bugs" - say what the bug is and how to avoid it
- **Avoid truisms:** If it's obviously true to anyone (e.g., "TDD catches bugs early"), either cut it or make it specific enough to be useful
- **"What This Means" and "What I Learned" are often bad titles:** They undersells your content thus far (the meaning should have been obvious) and insults the reader's intelligence (they should have gotten the meaning by now). Conclusions should crystallize and tie together, not just rehash - their section titles should therefore be similarly interesting.

## Blog-Specific Syntax

- Links don't render well when they link a blockquote; instead of [`<something>`](https://...), just use `<something>` or [something](https://...)

## Source Citations

If a source is introduced as a subject of discussion, it should be linked prominently the first time it is mentioned. This is normally with an anchor link, but `{% linkcard %}` may be used if the whole section is explicitly *about* the source. If the source has a really salient single graphic, the `{%polaroid %}` tag may be used to pull that graphic inline and link to the source.

Subsequent *references* to claims that a source supports should be indicated with markdown footnotes. Within the same section/paragraph where a paper is introduced and anchor-linked, claims from that paper do not need their own footnotes; the source is implied. However, if a section introduces multiple papers with anchor text, subsequent claims from each of those papers *do* need a footnote to disambiguate *which* claim is backed up by *which* paper. Similarly, claims later on in the document (far removed from the immediate context of the source) should be footnoted to indicate the authority they come from.

If a cited source ends up having both a prominent intro link and at least one footnote, use markdown reference links to DRY up the citation:

~~~markdown
Some [Paper Name][1] says claim... and other claim [^1].
This is interesting because ...

[1]: https://paper.com
[^1]: Paper Name, Author et. al. YYYY. [https://paper.com][1]
~~~

If a source is merely *cited* as a supporting authority for a claim, it should be footnoted *only*, without anchor text:

~~~markdown
It's been found that Some Claim[^1] and thefore I draw Some Conclusion.
About that Conclusion...

[^1]: Paper Name, Author et. al. YYYY. <https://paper.com>
~~~

Obviously, use correct and proper citation format for each source; the above examples just illustrate the markdown link techniques to use.

# Security

1. ALWAYS redact any sensitive information - including LAN and Local identifiers and information.
